error_codes.note: Standard HTTP error codes are listed below. Specific application-level error codes are unknown.

standard_error_responses.name: Bad Request
standard_error_responses.meaning: The request was invalid or cannot be served. This often occurs due to missing required parameters or invalid data format in the request body.

standard_error_responses.name: Unauthorized
standard_error_responses.meaning: Authentication failed. The request lacks valid authentication credentials (e.g., missing or expired token).

standard_error_responses.name: Forbidden
standard_error_responses.meaning: The server understood the request but refuses to authorize it. The authenticated user does not have the necessary permissions for this resource.

standard_error_responses.name: Not Found
standard_error_responses.meaning: The requested resource does not exist.

standard_error_responses.name: Method Not Allowed
standard_error_responses.meaning: The HTTP method used is not supported for this resource (e.g., trying to POST to a read-only endpoint).

standard_error_responses.name: Too Many Requests
standard_error_responses.meaning: Rate limit exceeded. The client has sent too many requests in a given amount of time.

standard_error_responses.name: Internal Server Error
standard_error_responses.meaning: A generic error occurred on the server side. This usually indicates a bug or unexpected condition.

error.description: A brief, human-readable description of the error.
